  "prompt": "What is the oldest book ever written?",
  "response": "Determining the \"oldest book ever written\" depends largely on how one defines a \"book.\" If we consider a book to be a collection of written texts bound together, the definition evolves over time. However, if we define a book as any substantial written work, several ancient texts are often cited as some of the oldest known written works in human history:\n\n### 1. **The Epic of Gilgamesh**\n- **Time Period:** Approximately 2100 BCE\n- **Origin:** Ancient Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq)\n- **Description:** Often regarded as the earliest surviving major literary work, the *Epic of Gilgamesh* is a series of Sumerian poems and later Akkadian versions that tell the story of Gilgamesh, the king of Uruk, and his adventures. Themes include friendship, the quest for immortality, and the human condition.\n\n### 2. **The Pyramid Texts**\n- **Time Period:** Circa 2400\u20132300 BCE\n- **Origin:** Ancient Egypt\n- **Description:** These are the oldest known religious texts in the world, inscribed on the walls of pyramids at Saqqara. The Pyramid Texts consist of spells or utterances intended to protect the pharaoh in the afterlife and assist in his resurrection.\n\n### 3. **The Rigveda**\n- **Time Period:** Composed between 1500 and 1200 BCE\n- **Origin:** Ancient India\n- **Description:** The *Rigveda* is one of the oldest known Vedic Sanskrit texts. It is a collection of hymns dedicated to various deities and is a foundational scripture of Hinduism.\n\n### 4. **The Enuma Elish**\n- **Time Period:** Circa 1100 BCE\n- **Origin:** Ancient Mesopotamia\n- **Description:** Also known as the Babylonian Creation Myth, this epic describes the creation of the world and the rise of the god Marduk to supremacy among the gods.\n\n### 5. **The Book of the Dead**\n- **Time Period:** Originated around 1550 BCE, with versions used until around 50 BCE\n- **Origin:** Ancient Egypt\n- **Description:** This is a collection of funerary texts consisting of spells, prayers, and incantations intended to guide the deceased through the afterlife.\n\n### Notable Mentions:\n- **Sumerian King List:** Dating back to around 2100 BCE, it is an ancient manuscript originally recorded in Sumerian language, listing kings of Sumer and their supposed reign lengths.\n- **The Tale of Sinuhe:** An ancient Egyptian narrative dating to around 1875 BCE, considered one of the finest works of literature from ancient Egypt.\n\n### Considerations:\n- **Material and Preservation:** Many of the earliest texts were inscribed on materials like clay tablets, papyrus, or stone, which have not all survived intact over millennia.\n- **Language and Script Evolution:** As writing systems evolved, so did the format and structure of literary works, complicating direct comparisons across different cultures and time periods.\n\n### Conclusion:\nWhile it's challenging to pinpoint a single \"oldest book,\" the *Epic of Gilgamesh* is frequently recognized as one of the oldest substantial literary works known to humanity. However, various ancient texts from Mesopotamia, Egypt, and India also vie for this distinction based on different criteria such as content, format, and historical context.",
  "response_tokens": [
